<p><em>Stephen Spiers is a Tattoo artist based in Glasgow, his psychedelic tattoos are vibrant and eye-catching, bringing fantasy art into reality.</em></p>



<div class="wp-block-columns">
<div class="wp-block-column">
<p>My grandfather had tattoos he’d had done in World War II, as a young child I thought they were great, a pin-up on his forearm that he would make dance by moving his arm; I’ve always remembered that.</p>



<p>In high school, I would design tattoos for the older kids; it wasn’t difficult to see that this was my main interest as I’d mostly be skipping class to sit in the library reading body modification/tattoo magazines. Everything else just seemed like a waste of time.</p>



<p>After a few years at college studying design, I started my tattoo apprenticeship. Back then, apprenticeships were rare and virtually impossible to get straight from school. After four years of apprenticing, I decided to travel, working in various shops around Europe as well as here in the UK.</p>
</div>



<div class="wp-block-column">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img width="812" height="1024" src="./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/03/ste1-812x1024.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-2373" srcset="./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/03/ste1-812x1024.jpg 812w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/03/ste1-768x969.jpg 768w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/03/ste1-1217x1536.jpg 1217w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/03/ste1-1320x1665.jpg 1320w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/03/ste1.jpg 1624w" sizes="(max-width: 812px) 100vw, 812px" /></figure>
</div>
</div>



<p> </p>



<p> I’ve now been tattooing for around 15 years. I opened my own studio in Glasgow, <a href="https://www.instagram.com/deviltowntattoo/?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Deviltown Tattoo</a>, four years ago. It’s given me the freedom to push my own boundaries in tattooing, going from more ‘traditional’ styles to a more contemporary outlook, which I’m enjoying very much. Throughout my career, I’ve tried to push my style in more creative directions. I find it hard to stick to a single style, I just can’t do it! Only now, after fifteen years, do I feel I have developed a recognisable technique.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1006" height="1024" src="./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/03/ste3-1006x1024.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-2387" srcset="./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/03/ste3-1006x1024.jpg 1006w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/03/ste3-768x782.jpg 768w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/03/ste3-1509x1536.jpg 1509w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/03/ste3-1320x1344.jpg 1320w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/03/ste3.jpg 2013w" sizes="(max-width: 1006px) 100vw, 1006px" /></figure>



<p><br>Tattooing is almost constantly on my mind, maybe more now than ever! I also paint a lot, taking inspiration from folk art, addiction, religion and psychedelia. I’m looking forward to continuing this journey and any experiences it throws at me.</p>



